===Crossovers=== {{Main|Law & Order (franchise)#Crossovers|Chicago (franchise)#Crossovers}} {{See also|Chicago Fire (TV series)#Crossovers|Chicago Med#Crossovers}}
*"Conventions" is the conclusion of a crossover with ''Law & Order: Special Victims Unit'' about the pursuit of a serial rapist. It features Amanda Rollins and Odafin Tutola, while "Comic Perversion" features Erin Lindsay. *"8:30 PM" is the conclusion of a crossover with ''Chicago Fire'' about an explosion that occurs at Chicago Med, leading the fire and police departments to track down the culprits. It features Matthew Casey, Kelly Severide, Wallace Boden, Leslie Shay, Peter Mills and Joe Cruz, while "A Dark Day" features Hank Voight, Antonio Dawson, Erin Lindsay, Jay Halstead, Kim Burgess and Kevin Atwater. *"They'll Have to Go Through Me" is the conclusion of a crossover with ''Chicago Fire'' and ''Law & Order: Special Victims Unit'' centered on a pedophile ring. It features Nick Amaro, Amanda Rollins and Olivia Benson, while "Nobody Touches Anything" features Hank Voight and Erin Lindsay, and "Chicago Crossover" features Erin Lindsay, Jay Halstead and Hank Voight. *"A Little Devil Complex" is the conclusion of a crossover with ''Chicago Fire'' about the pursuit of the arsonist who killed Leslie Shay.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2015/01/16/chicago-fire-chicago-pd-crossover-video/|title='Chicago Fire'-'Chicago P.D.' crossover first look: Shay's killer targets Dawson |work=Entertainment Weekly |accessdate=August 14, 2015}}</ref> It features Gabriela Dawson, Peter Mills and Wallace Boden, while "Three Bells" features Kim Burgess, Sean Roman and Antonio Dawson. *"The Number of Rats" is part two of a crossover with ''Chicago Fire'' and ''Law & Order: Special Victims Unit'' about a case of rape and murder in Chicago that resembles an unsolved case in New York.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvguide.com/news/chicago-fire-chicago-pd-svu-crossover/|title=Scoop: Another Chicago Fire-SVU-Chicago PD Crossover Coming This Year |first=Kate |last=Stanhope|date=January 23, 2015 |work=TVGuide.com |accessdate=August 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/walking-dead-alum-cast-chicago-786556|title='Walking Dead' Alum Cast on 'Chicago Fire' Crossover|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=August 14, 2015}}</ref> It features Olivia Benson, Nick Amaro, Odafin Tutuola and Dominick Carisi, Jr. from ''SVU'', as well as Matthew Casey and Wallace Boden from ''Fire'', while "We Called Her Jellybean" features Hank Voight and Antonio Dawson, and "Daydream Believer" features Hank Voight, Erin Lindsay, Jay Halstead, Kim Burgess and Sean Roman. * "Now I'm God" is the conclusion of a crossover with ''Chicago Fire'' and ''Chicago Med'' in which Christopher Herrmann is treated for a stab wound while a woman pulled from a fire is discovered to have been overdosed with chemotherapy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/listings/20151214nbc09/&date=01/06/2016|title=CHICAGO PD on NBC|work=The Futon Critic |accessdate=December 15, 2015}}</ref> It features Natalie Manning and Daniel Charles from ''Med,'' while "The Beating Heart" features Adam Ruzek, Kim Burgess and Trudy Platt, and "Malignant" features Jay Halstead and Erin Lindsay. * "The Song of Gregory Williams Yates" is the conclusion of a crossover with ''Law & Order: Special Victims Unit'' in which SVU helps Intelligence find escaped serial killer Greg Yates. It features Olivia Benson and Fin Tutuola, while "Nationwide Manhunt" features Antonio Dawson, Erin Lindsay and Hank Voight. * "Don't Bury This Case" is the conclusion of a crossover with ''Chicago Fire'' in which Kelly Severide is brought into the 21st after his car caused a deadly crash and the team finds a group of carjackers who may be the key to Severide's innocence. It features Matthew Casey, Kelly Severide, and Mouch from ''Fire'', while "Some Make It, Some Don't" features Erin Lindsay, Hank Voight, and Trudy Platt. * "Emotional Proximity" is part two of a crossover with ''Chicago Fire'' and ''Chicago Justice'' in which Firehouse 51 responds to the scene of a warehouse fire that puts the lives of many in danger, including a relative of a Chicago police officer. It features Will Halstead, Natalie Manning, and Ethan Choi from ''Med'', Kelly Severide, Wallace Boden, and Sylvie Brett from ''Fire'', and Antonio Dawson and Peter Stone from ''Justice'', while "Deathtrap" features Hank Voight, Alvin Olinsky, Erin Lindsay, and Kim Burgess, and "Fake" features Hank Voight and Alvin Olinsky. * "Endings" is part three of a crossover with ''Chicago Fire'' "Going to War" and ''Chicago Med'' "When to Let Go" where one of the patients at ''Chicago Med'' goes missing following a 22-story apartment fire. The Intelligence unit discovers that the patient had extracted a chip from her body leading to believe that she had been tracked and involved in trafficking ring.
===Spin-off=== {{Main|Chicago Justice}} At the 2016 [[Television Critics Association]] winter press tour, NBC Entertainment president Jennifer Salke revealed that the network had discussions with Dick Wolf about a fourth series in the ''Chicago'' franchise centered on the legal system. The working title was ''Chicago Law''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/chicago-law-nbc-dick-wolf-medical-p-d-1201679085/|title='Chicago Law' Could Be Fourth Installment of NBC Drama Franchise|publisher=Variety|last=Littleton|first=Cynthia|accessdate=January 13, 2016}}</ref> Salke has since confirmed that the series was officially in development.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/news/chicago-law-nbc-spinoff-dick-wolf-med-fire-pd/|title=Chicago Law Is In Development at NBC|publisher=TVGuide.com|last=Raftery|first=Liz|accessdate=January 21, 2016}}</ref> The series will be a spin-off of ''Chicago P.D.'' by introducing Assistant State's Attorney (ASA) characters in the 21st episode of ''P.D.'''s third season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/01/chicago-law-spinoff-coming-together-nbc-dick-wolf-1201687512/|title=Legal 'Chicago' Spinoff 'Chicago Law' From Dick Wolf Coming Together At NBC|website=Deadline Hollywood|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie}}</ref> [[Philip Winchester]] was the first to be cast.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/02/philip-winchester-star-chicago-law-spinoff-nbc-1201705912/|title=Philip Winchester To Star In 'Chicago Law' NBC Spinoff|website=Deadline Hollywood|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie}}</ref> [[Nazneen Contractor]] joined the series in March 2016 and the title was changed to ''Chicago Justice''.<ref>[http://tvline.com/2016/03/12/chicago-law-spinoff-justice-nazneen-contractor/ Chicago Law Spinoff Changes Name to Chicago Justice, Adds Reborn Hero]</ref> ''[[Rocky (film series)|Rocky]]'' alum [[Carl Weathers]] will play Cook County State's Attorney Mark Jefferies, while [[Joelle Carter]] will also star.<ref>{{cite web|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|url=http://deadline.com/2016/03/chicago-justice-carl-weathers-cast-chicago-pd-spinoff-nbc-1201723215|title='Chicago Justice': Carl Weathers Joins NBC's Legal 'Chicago' Spinoff|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=January 28, 2016|accessdate=March 20, 2016}}</ref> [[Lorraine Toussaint]] reprised her role as defense attorney Shambala Green, who appeared in seven episodes of ''[[Law & Order]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/lorraine-toussaint-set-chicago-justice-876909|title='Orange Is the New Black's' Lorraine Toussaint Set for 'Chicago Justice' (Exclusive)|work=The Hollywood Reporter|last=Stanhope|first=Kate|date=March 21, 2016}}</ref> On May 12, 2016, NBC gave ''Chicago Justice'' a series order.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2016/05/12/chicago-justice-ordered-to-series-by-nbc-in-2016-17/|title='Chicago Justice' ordered to series by NBC in 2016–17|last=Welch|first=Alex|work=TV by the Numbers|date=May 12, 2015|accessdate=May 12, 2016}}</ref> On September 28, it was reported that Jon Seda would join the cast and that his character Antonio would become an investigator for the DA's office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/09/jon-seda-chicago-pd-exit-move-chicago-justice-series-regular-antonio-dawson-1201827329/|title='Chicago P.D.' Star Jon Seda Moving To 'Chicago Justice' As Series Regular|website=Deadline Hollywood|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=September 28, 2016}}</ref> The series premiered on March 1, 2017. NBC canceled the series after one season.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://deadline.com/2017/05/chicago-justice-canceled-nbc-one-season-1202099623/|title=‘Chicago Justice’ Canceled By NBC After One Season|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=May 23, 2017|website=Deadline Hollywood|access-date=July 20, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> In July 2017, it was announced that Seda would rejoin ''Chicago P.D.'' full time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tvguide.com/news/chicago-pd-jon-seda-antonio-dawson-final-episode-justice/|title=Chicago P.D.'s Jon Seda Teases Antonio's Impending Exit|date=October 3, 2016|work=TVGuide.com|access-date=July 21, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Jon Seda Returns to 'Chicago PD' for Season 5|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/jon-seda-chicago-pd-season-5-1202494121/|accessdate=July 13, 2017}}</ref>
==Production== On March 27, 2013, it was reported that NBC was considering plans for a [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] of ''Chicago Fire''. [[Deadline Hollywood]] revealed that the proposed spin-off would involve the Chicago Police Department, and would be created and executive produced by [[Dick Wolf]], [[Derek Haas]], [[Michael Brandt]], and [[Matt Olmstead]].<ref name="CFSpinoff">{{cite web |url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/03/chicago-fire-spinoff-series-in-works-nbc |title=NBC Eyes 'Chicago Fire' Spinoff Series |last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=March 27, 2013|accessdate=March 27, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvline.com/2013/03/27/chicago-fire-spinoff-pilot-nbc |title=Chicago Fire Spreading? NBC Considering Police-Centric Spinoff Series |last=Slezak |first=Michael |publisher=[[TVLine]] |date=March 27, 2013|accessdate=March 27, 2013}}</ref> On May 10, 2013, NBC picked up the show for the [[2013–14 United States network television schedule]].<ref name=NpuCFsCP>{{cite web |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/tv/chi-chicago-pd-nbc-20130510,0,5511925.column|title=NBC picks up 'Chicago Fire' spinoff 'Chicago PD' |last=Metz|first=Nina |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=May 10, 2013|accessdate=May 11, 2013}}</ref> On May 12, 2013, the show was announced as an unscheduled midseason replacement.<ref name="NBC Sunday">{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/05/12/nbc-2013-2014-schedule-revolution-goes-to-wednesday-grimm-dracula-pair-for-friday-parenthood-thursday-biggest-loser-chicago-fire-to-tuesdays/182261/ |title=NBC 2013–2014 Schedule: 'Revolution' Goes to Wednesday, 'Grimm' & 'Dracula' Pair for Friday, 'Parenthood' Thursday + 'Biggest Loser' & 'Chicago Fire' to Tuesdays|last=Kondolojy|first=Amanda |publisher=[[TV by the Numbers]] |date=May 12, 2013|accessdate=May 12, 2013}}</ref> On October 18, 2013, NBC announced that it would premiere on January 8, 2014, at 10:00&nbsp;p.m. EST, after ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]''.<ref name="Chicago PD">{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/10/18/nbc-yanks-ironside-community-to-premiere-january-2-chicago-p-d-january-8/210019/ |title='Ironside' & 'Welcome to the Family' Canceled by NBC; 'Community' to Premiere January 2, 'Chicago P.D.' January 8|last=Bibel|first=Sara |publisher=[[TV by the Numbers]] |date=October 18, 2013|accessdate=October 18, 2013}}</ref>
On November 9, 2015, NBC renewed the series for a fourth season,<ref name="Chicago Fire & Chicago PD renewed">{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2015/11/09/chicago-fire-and-chicago-pd-renewed-for-2016-17-at-nbc/|title='Chicago Fire' & 'Chicago P.D.' Renewed For 2016–17 at NBC|last=Porter|first=Rick|work=TV by the Numbers|date=November 9, 2015|accessdate=November 9, 2015}}</ref> which premiered on September 21, 2016.<ref name="Season 4">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/nbc-fall-tv-show-premiere-date-2016-2017-season-the-voice-blindspot-the-blacklist-1201796211/|title=NBC Sets Fall Premiere Dates for 2016–17 Season|last=Prudom|first=Lauren|work=Variety|date=June 15, 2016|accessdate=June 15, 2016}}</ref> On May 10, 2017, NBC renewed the series for a fifth season, which premiered on September 27, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/05/chicago-fire-chicago-pd-chicago-med-renewed-no-decision-justice-1202089222/|title='Chicago Fire', 'Chicago PD' & 'Chicago Med' Renewed, No Decision On 'Justice'|website=Deadline Hollywood|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=May 10, 2017|accessdate=May 10, 2017}}</ref><ref name="NBC Fall Premiere Dates">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2017/06/19/nbc-announces-fall-premiere-dates-for-new-2017-18-season-720212/20170619nbc02/|title=NBC Announces Fall Premiere Dates for New 2017–18 Season|work=[[The Futon Critic]]|date=June 19, 2017|accessdate=June 19, 2017}}</ref>
===Filming=== The series is filmed entirely in [[Chicago]]. The exterior of the station house is the [[7th District Police Station|Old Maxwell Street Police Station]] (943 West Maxwell Street) and is the same location that was used on the series ''[[Hill Street Blues]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1998-03-15/features/9803150456_1_dungeon-city-police-unit-brick |title=The Old Red Ship |first=Gary |last=Moore |work=Chicago Tribune |date=March 15, 1998 |accessdate=January 7, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://police.uic.edu/History%20of%20Maxwell%20Street%20Station.htm |title=History of Maxwell Street Station |website=University Of Illinois @ Chicago Police Department |accessdate=January 7, 2016}}</ref> It is located about half a mile from the firehouse location of ''Chicago Fire'' at 1360 S. Blue Island Ave.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.onlocationvacations.com/2015/08/13/where-is-the-firehouse-from-chicago-fire/ |title=Where is the firehouse from 'Chicago Fire'? |website=On Location Vacations |date=August 13, 2015 |accessdate=January 7, 2016 |author=Christine}}</ref>
===Casting=== [[Tania Raymonde]] was cast in the planned series as a police officer named Nicole. [[Kelly Blatz]] was also cast as a young but seasoned Officer Elam.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/04/kelly-blatz-cast-in-chicago-fire-spinoff |title=Kelly Blatz Cast In 'Chicago Fire' Spinoff |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=April 10, 2013|accessdate=April 16, 2013}}</ref> The new characters were introduced in the penultimate episode of ''Chicago Fire'''s first season, which aired on May 15, 2013.<ref name=NpuCFsCP/> [[Scott Eastwood]] was set to portray Officer Jim Barnes in the ''Chicago Fire'' season finale and the proposed spin-off. Eastwood also co-starred with Tania Raymonde in ''[[Texas Chainsaw 3D]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvline.com/2013/04/09/chicago-fire-spinoff-cast-scott-eastwood-nbc|title=Chicago Fire Exclusive: Scott Eastwood (aka Clint's Son) Joins Police-Focused Spin-Off |last=Ausiello |first=Michael |work=[[TVLine]] |date=April 9, 2013 |accessdate=April 9, 2013}}</ref> ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|Law & Order: SVU's]]'' [[Melissa Sagemiller]] would portray Detective Willhite, a member of the Chicago P.D. Intelligence Unit.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/04/melissa-sagemiller-to-star-in-nbcs-chicago-fire-spinoff |title=Melissa Sagemiller To Star In NBC's 'Chicago Fire' Spinoff |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=April 10, 2013 |accessdate=April 21, 2013}}</ref> Other cast members include [[Jason Beghe]] as the Intelligence team Sergeant Hank Voight and [[Jon Seda]] as Detective Antonio Dawson.<ref name=NSO>{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/nbc-series-orders-chicago-fire-520712 |title=NBC Series Orders: 'Chicago Fire' Spinoff, 'Ironside' Remake, 'Undateable' |last1=Goldberg |first1=Lesley |last2=Rose |first2=Lacey |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=May 10, 2013 |accessdate=May 11, 2013}}</ref> LaRoyce Hawkins was the only Chicago area actor originally cast in May.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.suntimes.com/entertainment/television/20111560-421/the-personal-lives-of-police-at-the-heart-of-chicago-fire-spinoff.html |title=The personal lives of police at the heart of 'Chicago Fire' spinoff |accessdate=October 17, 2013 |date=May 14, 2013 |work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |last=Rackl |first=Lori}}</ref>
As the show went into pre-production, the cast began to change. On June 13, 2013, it was announced that [[Melissa Sagemiller]] would no longer be a part of the show and [[Jesse Lee Soffer]] officially joined the cast as a series regular. His character was introduced in the second season of ''[[Chicago Fire (TV series)|Chicago Fire]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2013/06/jesse-lee-soffer-joins-nbcs-chicago-pd-as-regular-gets-arc-on-chicago-fire-526319/ |title=Jesse Lee Soffer Joins NBC's 'Chicago PD' As Regular, Gets Arc On 'Chicago Fire' |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=June 20, 2013 |accessdate=January 7, 2016}}</ref> On August 23, 2013, [[Patrick Flueger]] and ''[[One Tree Hill (TV Series)|One Tree Hill]]'' star [[Sophia Bush]] joined the cast as Officer Adam Ruzek and Detective Erin Lindsay respectively.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/sophia-bush-patrick-flueger-join-613592 |title=Sophia Bush, Patrick Flueger Join NBC's 'Chicago PD' |last=Goldberg |first=Lesley |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=August 23, 2013 |accessdate=January 7, 2016}}</ref> Marina Squerciati joined the cast on August 28, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/08/nbcs-chicago-pd-adds-another-regualar/ |title=NBC's 'Chicago PD' Adds Another Regular |accessdate=October 17, 2013|date=August 28, 2013 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie}}</ref> On August 30, [[Elias Koteas]] became a regular.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/killings-elias-koteas-boards-chicago-618515 |title='The Killing's' Elias Koteas Boards 'Chicago PD' (Exclusive) |accessdate=October 17, 2013 |date=August 30, 2013 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |last=Goldberg |first=Lesley}}</ref> [[Archie Kao]] was announced as a regular on September 27, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/09/archie-kao-joins-chicago-pd-as-regular-genevieve-angelson-in-house-of-lies/ |title=Archie Kao Joins 'Chicago PD' As Regular; Genevieve Angelson In 'House Of Lies' |accessdate=October 17, 2013 |date=September 27, 2013 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie}}</ref>
On October 21, 2013, [[Stella Maeve]] was cast in a recurring role as Nadia, a pretty 18-year-old escort who is addicted to heroin and goes through a very difficult withdrawal.<ref>{{cite web |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |title=Stella Maeve Joins 'Chicago PD'; Nick Tarabay Cast In 'Believe'; 'Gang Related' & 'Twisted' Also Add Recurring |url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/10/stella-maeve-joins-chicago-pd-nick-tarabay-cast-in-believe-gang-related-twisted-also-add-recurring |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=November 3, 2013}}</ref> [[Sydney Tamiia Poitier]] will guest star in five episodes as a detective, who will eventually crossover on to ''Chicago Fire''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/12/sydney-t-poitier-chicago-pd-chicago-fire-tim-daly-hot-in-cleveland/|title=Sydney T. Poitier Gets 'Chicago PD'/ 'Chicago Fire' Role, Tim Daly Joins 'Hot In Cleveland' |website=Deadline Hollywood |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |date=December 2, 2013 |accessdate=December 4, 2013}}</ref> On December 20, 2013, it was announced that both Eastwood and Raymonde had departed the series over creative differences.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2013/12/20/chicago-pd-scott-eastwood-tania-raymonde-leaving-cast/ |title=Exclusive: ''Chicago Fire'' Spin-Off Cuts Two Actors |work=TV Line |last=Ausiello |first=Michael |date=December 20, 2013 |accessdate=December 21, 2013}}</ref>
On September 2016, it was reported that series regular [[Jon Seda]] would move to the new spin-off ''[[Chicago Justice]]'' as regular.<ref>{{cite web|title='Chicago P.D.' Star Jon Seda Moving to 'Justice' Spinoff as Series Regular|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/chicago-pd-jon-seda-moving-933618|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=September 28, 2017|date=September 28, 2016}}</ref> After ''Justice'''s cancellation, in July 2017 it was disclosed that Seda would move back to ''Chicago P.D.'' as series regular for season 5<ref>{{cite web|title='Chicago P.D.': Jon Seda to Return for Season 5|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/chicago-pd-jon-seda-moving-933618|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=September 28, 2017|date=July 12, 2017}}</ref>
In May 2017, it was announced that Sophia Bush would depart the series after four seasons<ref>{{cite web|title=Sophia Bush Leaving 'Chicago P.D.' After Four Seasons|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/sophia-bush-leaving-chicago-pd-1007813|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=September 28, 2017|date=May 25, 2017}}</ref>
In July 2017, [[Tracy Spiridakos]] was promoted to series regular as Det. Hailey Upton, after a two-episode guest stint in season 4.<ref>{{cite web|title='Chicago P.D.': Tracy Spiridakos Joins as Series Regular After Sophia Bush's Exit|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/chicago-pd-season-5-tracy-spiridakos-joins-cast-1024213|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=September 28, 2017|date=July 25, 2017}}</ref>
It came to light in November 2017 that Bush's exit was due to Jason Beghe's behavior behind the scenes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jason Beghe's Behavior Reportedly Led to Sophia Bush's 'Chicago P.D.' Exit|url=http://popculture.com/tv-shows/2017/11/22/jason-beghes-sophia-bush-chicago-p-d/|website=Pop Culture|accessdate=November 22, 2017|date=November 22, 2017}}</ref> Bush's claims lead NBC to open up an investigation into Beghe's behavior<ref>{{cite web|title=‘Chicago P.D.’s Jason Beghe Investigated By NBC For "Inappropriate Behavior" Amid Sexual Harassment Claims|url=http://deadline.com/2017/11/jason-beghe-chicago-pd-sophia-bush-sexual-harassment-allegations-nbc-investigation-1202213264/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=November 22, 2017|date=November 22, 2017}}</ref>
==Reception== Airing at 10 p.m. Wednesdays, ''Chicago P.D.'' is earning a 2.3 rating, 7 share in adults 18–49 and 9.4 million viewers overall this season, for gains versus last season of +10% in 18–49 and +14% in total viewers. ''Chicago P.D.'' has finished {{Abbr|No.|number}} 1 or tied for No. 1 among ABC, CBS and NBC in the time period with five of its last six original broadcasts through Feb. 2.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/02/blacklist-chicago-fire-chicago-pd-law-order-svu-grimm-renewed-nbc-1201366899/|title='Blacklist', 'Chicago Fire', 'Chicago PD', 'Law & Order: SVU' And 'Grimm' Renewed By NBC |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=February 5, 2015 |accessdate=January 7, 2016}}</ref>
