{{Other uses|Electro (disambiguation){{!}}Electro}} [[File:Senator John Heinz History Center - IMG 7802.JPG|right|180px|thumb|Elektro the Moto-Man and his Little Dog Sparko]] '''Elektro''' is the nickname of a [[robot]] built by the [[Westinghouse Electric Corporation]] in its [[Mansfield, Ohio]] facility between 1937 and 1938. Seven feet tall (2.1 m), weighing 265 pounds (120.2&nbsp;kg), humanoid in appearance, he could walk by voice command, speak about 700 words (using a 78-rpm [[phonograph|record player]]), smoke cigarettes, blow up balloons, and move his head and arms. Elektro's body consisted of a steel gear, cam and motor skeleton covered by an aluminum skin. His [[photodetector|photoelectric]] "eyes" could distinguish red and green light. He was on exhibit at the [[1939 New York World's Fair]] and reappeared at that fair in 1940, with "Sparko", a robot dog that could bark, sit, and beg to humans.
==History== Elektro toured North America in 1950 in promotional appearances for Westinghouse, and was displayed at [[Pacific Ocean Park]] in [[Venice, California]] in the late 1950s and early 1960s. He also appeared as "Thinko", in ''[[Sex Kittens Go to College]]'' (1960). In the 1960s, his head was given to Harold Gorsuch, a retiring Westinghouse engineer.
In 1992, the dance band [[Meat Beat Manifesto]] produced the song "Original Control (Version 2)" which prominently featured snippets of Elektro's monologues, quoting lines such as "I am Elektro" and "My brain is bigger than yours".
Elektro survived the scrap pile and is currently the property of the Mansfield Memorial Museum.<ref>[https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg20026873.000-the-return-of-elektro-the-first-celebrity-robot.html The Return of Electro], Jack Weeks, New Scientist</ref><ref>[https://www.npr.org/2012/04/02/149850779/americas-first-celebrity-robot-is-staging-a-comeback? America's First Celebrity Robot is Staging a Comeback], Emma Jacobs, National Rublic Radio</ref> In 2013, a replica of Elektro was exhibited at [[The Henry Ford]] Museum in [[Dearborn, MI]].<ref>{{cite web |publisher=The Henry Ford Museum |date=April 2013 |url=http://www.thehenryford.org/events/worldsFairsPreviewEvent.aspx |title=Designing Tomorrow: America’s World’s Fairs of the 1930s Exhibit Preview |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140220131724/http://www.thehenryford.org/events/worldsFairsPreviewEvent.aspx |archivedate=2014-02-20 |df= }}</ref>
A "Mansfield Museum of Circuitry and Robotics" and anecdotes about Elektro and Sparko are briefly but touchingly presented in the beginning of the novel ''The Man from Primrose Lane'' by James Renner, 2012, Sarah Crichton Books, an imprint of Farrar, Straus and Giroux.
